How to Measure

- Take a representative sample set of counters, and have people stand and observe behavior.

- Mystery audit of representative counters where you walk in to counters and pose generic and brand queries.

Things that you should measure

- % of Generic Queries in a Counter

- % of Brand Queries, measured for each brand

- Brand Introduced for Generic Queries

- Brand Introduced for Brand Queries

As a brand, you need to ensure that your brand is always introduced for your brand queries.

And whenever competition is out of stock/having an engagement issue, your brand should be introduced by the shopkeeper even for competition brand queries

Brand queries almost always results in introduction of the same brand as the chances of conversion is higher.

But similar to how Amazon search ads with competition targeting works( SP ads on comp KWs), there are 2 occasions when the retailer introduces a competition brand

But unlike an Amazon, retailers will never introduce brands for generic queries( even with high margins) if they think the chances of conversion is poor

To solve this, brands need to ensure that the retailer is engaged and has confidence on the brand

The response to the generic queries by the retailer is also similar to how Amazon Search works.

For any keyword, Amazon organically shows those SKUs which has the highest chance of conversion. Similarly the retailer also introduces that brand which he thinks will convert best

You should understand what % of the queries are generic and what % are brand.

Amongst brand, you should understand your queries compared to competition queries

For a consumer looking for ceiling fans, these could be the queries

- Generic Queries: Consumer comes and asks the shopkeeper to show premium ceiling fans

- Brand Queries: Consumer comes and asks the shopkeeper for Atomberg

Select name from customers where (select count(*) from orders O where https://t.co/VW4I9ZYplR = O.customerID)  > 5

An example:
Select name from customers where https://t.co/d4EOwdGOCi in (select distinct customerID from orders)
A simple query to get all customers who have orders. If cached, complexity is O(n*m). Same as an inner join on customerID
